          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/lotr/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="0" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Houston, TX  4/27/02<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7725'>Niado "The Factory" Duegad</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7725&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Tournament- 4/27/02  Midnight Comics, Houston, TX<br>
(its been a little while, can&#8217;t remember all the details of the games)<br>
<br>
	This was my first tournament, although I had been playing the game since the beginning.  Since I started playing, I have gone through many different deck types, but I decided I needed something solid.  I went for Gandalf direct archery with the usual tricks like SoS, and SotSF.  For my shadow side, I went with the tried and true Moria swarm with complimentary cave trolls and Balrog, 4 armories, etc.  I have a habit of getting tired of decks VERY easily, but this one had been doing so solidly that I had to use it for my first tournament.  In playtesting, I had mainly been winning by reaching site nine first, but that was because I had been playing against my friend&#8217;s invincible hobbit fellowship (I once played 7 or 8 orcs plus troll w/ hammer at site 7, only one person died!).  My fellowship has the most trouble with Uruk-hai, but at least my moria can slow the opponent down enough to keep me ahead.  The night before the tournament, I had one of my friends over, Daryll, who was fairly new at the game (only played 2 games before), and tried to show him how to play like a master in a few hours (I failed).  I built him a gandalf/men &#8211; nazgul deck, but if I write much more about this, and he reads this report, he might kill me.  (He didn&#8217;t understand after the tournament that it wasn&#8217;t a bad deck, only he didn&#8217;t have much experience.)<br>
<br>
	All three of us (me, Daryll, and Allen) got to Midnight Comics around 11:50, because it was supposed to start at noon.  The TD informed us that the info posted on Decipher was wrong, so we chilled for an hour.  Soon after we got there, some other guys arrived from San Antonio.  (We aren&#8217;t exactly &#8216;hard-core&#8217; players, we&#8217;re still in high school, and don&#8217;t exactly go around the U.S. to play LOTR.).  The fact that they had driven down to Houston from San Antonio, and were going to Georgia next week just to play LOTR was very intimidating to us.  One of them came over wanting to trade, and seemed very thrilled about some random cheesy foils I had.  I was very willing, because I got a badly needed PATHS, and SotSF out of the deal.  Also, luckily I never had to play Allen, because we play each other all the time, and know each other&#8217;s deck by heart.  On to the games.<br>
<br>
Round 1:  vs. Daniel&#8217;s shiny huge fellowship/sauron madness<br>
<br>
First game I get paired against the guy I traded with, and now I see why he wanted foils.  His whole deck was foily! (almost).  He started all of the hobbits (all rare except pip), and bid 2 or 3.  I bid 5, as always, and start Gandalf & frodo (both mines of moria version).  My first site is the Sam Hotel, and Sam is released to remove 3 burdens.  Aragorn KIE comes from my hand, (I have 4 in my deck because he is so key) and I move to the troll forest.  He plays an inquisitor (didn&#8217;t expect anyone to play sauron, that was the only deck-type I hadn&#8217;t tested against.), and discards something pointless.  Then he plays a desperate defense on Aragorn, so Gandalf comes and fights, takes a wound, and I stop.  He plays a foil gray pilgrim, and I think also a rare Aragorn.  He moves, and I don&#8217;t play much, he presses on to site 3, I just give them the normal roaming/not set up yet moria stuff, plus I get out an armory and swarms.  My turn, I play a rare legolas,(my fellowship is now set up), and move to 3.  This was very intense.  He played a couple of trackers, I think &#8216;no big deal&#8217; and assign Aragorn (gandalf now has a DDotR, and Frodo is looking very thin and stretched) and add a burden.  I then assign the Frod to his power 6 assassin so frodo wouldn&#8217;t get even more stretched.  Totally forgot about the Enduring Evil that I should have seen coming, as I used to play Sauron myself.  Now Frodo is power 2 to his 6, and I don&#8217;t have a bounder or anything yet.  Oh boy, this is going to be a long day, I thought...then I remembered I had his PATHS in my hand, and that saved me the game.  From there on out, it was a war of attrition between him and me, but I managed to keep removing burdens via Sam, and he didn&#8217;t appear to have any hates (he probably had 10 normal, just no foil), and without that kinda stuff, Sauron isn&#8217;t too masterful at stopping or killing.  I slept away his DDotR&#8217;s so that was good for me.  Also my archery was destroying him w/ the Saga and Tale on Aragorn/Legolas.  I killed some companions, but he had so many it didn&#8217;t matter.  From there on out, I didn&#8217;t have much of a problem making it to site 9.<br>
<br>
FW +3 (1-0)<br>
Highs:<br>
	+Winning my first ever tournament game<br>
	+Daniel, for having so many foils<br>
	+Daniel, for trading me PATHS<br>
	+PATHS<br>
Lows:<br>
	-Me for almost losing my first game at site 3<br>
	-Me for not realizing until a few days ago that Sam<br>
         would&#39;ve taken the ring<br>
	-Daniel, for not having hates.  That would&#8217;ve made <br>
         things tricky<br>
<br>
Round 2: vs. Joel&#8217;s Frodo/Rare Aragorn duet &#8211; moria swarm<br>
<br>
This game was pretty weird.  I started first again, and pretty much went one site a turn (game only lasted until site 6). I couldn&#8217;t afford to double move, because he always had a troll waiting for me in his hand (thank you sting).  His Aragorn was pretty loaded up, with sword, bow, saga, armor, etc.  The death blow came at the Bridge, when I got out a troll w/ hammer and chain plus a runner.  He couldn&#8217;t gun down the troll because of the chain.  Frodo stealthed the first troll, but Mr. Troll decided that he had to finish the job, so he came back around for aragorn, and overwhelmed him.  That shot him bad, because the next site was dimril dale, where I got out 5 or 6 orcs on his lone Frodo, and he had no PATHS.<br>
<br>
FW +3 (2-0)<br>
Highs:<br>
	+Getting out troll with hammer and chain<br>
	+winning with my shadow side<br>
Lows:<br>
	+kinda short game.  Of course 2 companions isn&#8217;t so <br>
         good against moria.<br>
<br>
Daniel was playing his game next to me, and I saw him play 4 enduring evils on frodo in one skirmish.  Quite deadly.<br>
<br>
Round 3: vs. some master who I can&#8217;t remember his name&#8217;s Rare Gandalf w/ all 5 species &#8211; nazgul with swords<br>
<br>
This was by far the hardest game, and he should&#8217;ve won (whoops, just gave away the ending).  I bid 5 to his 4, and went first.  He seemed quite distraught, until he saw I started the Sam Station also.  I drew a Leg-o-meat (greenleaf), but no Aragorn.  This game was very unlucky for both of us, as I never drew any of my flaming brands or ranger&#8217;s swords.  For him, well just wait.  I moved to the weatherhills, and faced an Ulaire Attea with sword.  What a beast, he could pump up to 14, just enough to overwhelm Gandalf.  Gand went in first, and told Attea that he was a servant of the secret fire.  After some thought, Attea decided that he would like a feast, so he came back.  He got his feast with some delicious Sam, as I hadn&#8217;t drawn another SotSF (or if I had drawn one of my 4 SoS, Attea could have been shot.  Or if I had drawn one of my 4 Aragorns...).  I had to stop because Sam didn&#8217;t seem to satisfy Attea&#8217;s hunger, and a ford was in the distance.  This ended up being a very slow game, as we both had to move one site a turn.  For him, I got out some random orcs, but he obviously stopped at 2 to get his ford out.  I pressed on to the ford, (still no Aragorn) but I did give legolas a tale of gil-galad.  ANOTHER Attea busted out, but no sword, so he bit gandalf twice and I stopped.  We both made it past the bridge going one site a turn, hard pressed to deal with each other&#8217;s minions, although he was making good use of intimidates to deal with cave trolls.  At site 6, I had to face a witch king.  This was the most intense moment in the tournament, as I hadn&#8217;t drawn ANY pumpers, and still no Aragorn.  All I had was my exhausted Gandalf, Leg, and Frodo.  I did have 2 PATHS, though.  If I didn&#8217;t want to lose anyone, I would have to shoot the King twice, and then PATHS him twice.  I shot twice, but Legolas was informed that All Blades Perish, so he was forced to shoot again (thanks to the tale).  Then I realize &#8216;oh boy, if he has another ABP, I lose.&#8217;  I went for it, and he made me quite nervous when I asked him if he had anything to play.  But, he doesn&#8217;t, so the Witchy finds out that the ring had given Frodo twice the power according to his stature, and he shrieks, &#8220;but that would mean I would have to be...&#8221;  Frodo turns into Max Zorin and says, &#8220;Dead&#8221;.  Finally, I draw an Aragorn (if you&#8217;re wondering what my shadow has been doing, not much, but at least forcing him to stop every turn.  He was able to double from 6 to 8, though, forcing me the deadly double jump from 7 to 9), and give him a bow, had to stop at site 7 because of Cantea.  At site 8, I encountered Toldea with his targeting computer active.  Toldea decided that he would make a relentless charge.  Obviously not satisfied, Toldea gave Legolas a personalized invitation, which leg accepted.  Legolas was now exhausted, and I was about ready to put him in the trash can, when Toldea&#8217;s targeting computer malfunctioned, and he chose Aragorn.  Not quite sure what that did, but all the better for me.  I had to move again to site nine, because I couldn&#8217;t destroy his fellowship.  It was the Summit, and he drew 4 extra cards, but he got supremely unlucky and didn&#8217;t draw anything.  Now I realize that he went after Aragorn in hopes of drawing a relentless charge, which would have killed Aragorn and Leg.  But, he didn&#8217;t draw anything, so I survived.<br>
<br>
FW +3 (3-0)<br>
Highs:<br>
	+His shadow side, I loved the raw power (Attea w/ <br>
         sword)<br>
	+PATHS<br>
	+Sam for being so delicious<br>
Lows:<br>
	-His luck<br>
	-my luck<br>
	-Aragorn for being late<br>
	-no flaming brands the whole game (have 2, almost <br>
         went through my entire deck<br>
	-him for playing ABP, if he had saved it until <br>
         skirmish, he would have won<br>
	-almost running out of time<br>
<br>
I was the only player who had gone 3-0 so far, no one else was doing too well (despite the fact that many of the players were ranked pretty high, one guy was one of the top in TX, but had gone 1-2 so far).  Daryll&#8217;s status: 0-3, and telling me how bad the deck I made for him was, and how horrible nazgul were, despite the fact that I had almost just gotten slaughtered by nazgul.  Because Daniel was the guy that had done the best besides me, we ended up playing each other again.<br>
<br>
Round 4: vs. Daniel again<br>
<br>
The TD informed me that if I won this game, there would be no final confrontation, but if I lost, the final confrontation would be me vs....Daniel AGAIN!  At least I knew that I was able to beat him.  This time, I bid 4, because I knew he had 4 enduring evils, so sam could get me down to one.  He bids 4 also, and wins the coin toss; he goes first = total slaughter.  My deck gets shot hard when I don&#8217;t go first.  He started the pony, but I knew I couldn&#8217;t use it because I couldn&#8217;t add any more burdens than I already had.  Luckily I drew Aragorn in my hand, so I didn&#8217;t have to use the pony, or go with only gandalf and frodo.  My shadow is about the same as the first game up to site three- like moria always is before it gets cookin&#8217;.  I made it to site three with no casualties, but Legolas hadn&#8217;t shown up yet.  Aragorn was equiped with bow and sword, in other words, ready for the action packed mines of moria.  Daniel washimmer pretty hard going over the next few sites, as the cave troll dropped by with hammer and chain.  Also, the balrog wanted in on the action, so he had his fun at site 5, you get the picture. However, it didn&#8217;t matter much, as he had so much meat to feed to my minions.  I made it through moria quite painlessly, lucky for me, he hadn&#8217;t drawn his enduring evils yet, as Sam hadn&#8217;t made his appearance yet, and I was at 4 burdens.  He did get some DDotR on me, but I slept it away at site 6, which was also where legolas, and Sam (thank you!!) joined me.  (no we didn&#8217;t both just triple move from 3 to 6, but I didn&#8217;t feel like writing it out turn by turn.)  He was ahead of me in the race now, since he had gone first.  At both sites 7 and 8, the cave troll came out, both times with hammer (via relics of moria).  At 8, he was complimented by 5 orcs, stopping him, and allowing me to move to nine.  Nothing special at site 9, almost an exact repeat of the first game.  Fully healed Aragorn with bow and saga/legolas with tale shot most of the orcs (would&#8217;ve been tough otherwise, with 2 band of the eye, etc.), and Gandalf, Aragorn came in and took care of the rest (although Gandalf got 3 enduring evils and had to leave).<br>
<br>
FW +3 (4-0)<br>
Highs:<br>
	+Cave troll did his job<br>
	+barely got out 5 orcs to stop Daniel, drew my 5th <br>
	 one with a scimitar<br>
        +Daniel for killing Gandalf with 3 enduring evils<br>
Lows:<br>
	+Playing the same person twice, although Daniel was<br>
         very fun to play<br>
 	+Sam for being late, and not available at the Sam <br>
         hotel<br>
	+me for shooting all of his orcs that he worked so <br>
         hard to put out<br>
<br>
So I won the tournament, being the only player to go 4-0.<br>
<br>
Me &#8211;1st<br>
Nazgul Master &#8211; 2nd<br>
Daniel &#8211; 3rd<br>
Joel &#8211; 3rd<br>
Allen &#8211; 3rd<br>
Giang &#8211; 4th<br>
Some guy I didn&#8217;t play &#8211; 5th<br>
Daryll &#8211; 6th (sorry, maybe you should have paid more attention in Statistics class...)<br>
<br>
However, I was compensated for my good fortune because my packs for winning first were so poor. (I chose the packs because the foil choices were also pretty poor, and I&#8217;m too greedy to wait for a random foil in the mail, now I know better)<br>
<br>
For the entire tournament:<br>
<br>
Highs:<br>
	+Winning (of course)<br>
